{
  "answer": "**I could not find any couplet by Ghalib (or in *Diwan-e-Ghalib*) that uses the specific image of a \"candle's tongue\" combined with a \"moth's prayer\" (or close variants like \"lamp,\" \"flame,\" \"parwana\"/\"moth,\" \"tongue,\" or \"prayer\").**\n\nThe corpus includes the full *Diwan-e-Ghalib* (239 chapters in English translation), but extensive searches across key terms (\"candle,\" \"moth,\" \"lamp,\" \"tongue,\" \"prayer,\" and combinations) returned zero matching results in this work.[^1] The candle/moth (*sham'a-parwana*) motif is common in Urdu poetry (e.g., appearing in Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara*), but it does not appear here in the described form.[^2]\n\nIf this refers to a specific sher/ghazal not captured in this translation or outside the Falsafa corpus's 37 works, it is not available for citation. You may provide more details (e.g., the Urdu original) for further checks.",
